76561198011604006,Recommended,246760,18677016,"Posted: 25 October, 2015",all,Saboth,"LoE is an rpg/strategy game in the vein of ""King's Bounty"" or ""Heroes of MM"".  You explore maps with a single party, avoiding powerful enemies while picking off weaker ones.  Your main character levels up, and any characters you have level up as well. This takes place in a low-fantasy setting. You'll run into some creatures here and there, but there are no dragons or anything like that. I was on the fence about recommending the game, because as fun as it is, there are a lot of frustrations as well.Good:Graphics, story, combat gameplay, gear/upgrades, sound.Bad: Heal mechanic, exp gain is slow, quests can be obtuse (either the quest is not well explained, or the triggers can take a long time to find).All-in-all, it's addictive, and mostly fun, but the frustrations that are present seem largely unecessary."
76561198042113156,Recommended,246760,20005703,"Posted: 27 December, 2015",all,cfranks007,"This looks pretty good so far. I've watched some Youtube Let's Play by Kill Ten Rats and he does a good job. Apparently the exp was decreased after some of his first Let's Play videos (bonus to the Early Access players).So, what is this game? It is a medieval fantasy RPG where you are a German noble trying to retake his rightful lands. You have to build an army, defeat enemies and capture castles. You are allowed to hire an army  that is sized based on the castles you control plus you can hire mercenaries (mercenaries can increase the size of the army beyond what you are allowed) but the mercenaries will deplete your gold fast because they also cost gold to maintain the troops. You and your troops can gain levels based on the experience you gain by fighting.Play is in real time except for combat which is turn based, based upon initiative. The graphics are nice and the music is not annoying (not yet anyhow). The storylines are very good so far (already got a good plot twist).In addition to running around trying to complete quests, you have to garrison your captured castles and watchtowers (if you can't garrison them, then you don't have control yet.).I haven't decided what to give this for a score because I have not finished it yet but it looks like it has a fair amount of replay even if you know what to do."
76561198067725186,Recommended,246760,20080742,"Posted: 29 December, 2015",all,hexagon,"This game is great! I’d compare it a little to Witcher II with the level of depth and detail.The backstory has been well thought out, and you really feel like you are playing a role in a larger plan.The rumors, and stories you hear and read about in the game are interesting, and I've read each of them. Usually in a game like Skyrim, I'd read a few, and then just skip the rest. The stories all tie in very well with the game and atmosphere, the writing is really top notch. There are some typos, and some bits that did not translate well to english, but you'll still catch the meaning.The combat system is easy to grasp and enjoyable. The rules are simple, but you must make use of some strategy to maximize the damage you can deal to the enemy, and prevent yourself from taking too much damage. Injured party members can be healed with spells, potions, and local temples, but those all cost money, and money is sometimes difficult to come by.If you play the game, read some of the forum post stickies as they offer additional insight into the game mechanics. There are also some YouTube videos that show some easy tips to follow. For instance, it was not until chapter 2 that I realized the map could rotate! The right mouse button is your friend in this game. RMB everything and see what it shows and does.One of my favorite parts of the game is the inventory system when you go into a market or store. It is just like most games with a buy/sell system, but if you click on a party member, the store items rearrange themselves and turn different colors. It is almost like each party member has a wishlist of the equipment they want. If you have the money, buy the green stuff at the top pf the list! This is so much better than reading and comparing stats between multiple weapons to determine if a certain sword is better than a certain heavy mace.My least favorite part of the game WAS starting over at each chapter. I say WAS, because now that I know to expect it, I can prepare for it. Sure, you lose your awesome party members that you trained from a lowly peasant to a war steed riding knight of death, but you get to do it all over again, and this time you’ll make even better choices. There are a few times when you get to carry over two party members, so you don't always have to start fresh.I finished the game in 54 hours. I'm planning to play through again and see if I can find some of the stuff I missed on the first playthrough.I got stuck at one battle in the game (chapter 4?), and was unable to go any further without cheating. I'm sure this is because I'm not great with the combat tactitcs yet. The developer put some combat scenarios on his site to go through, and I'm unable to beat the first one... Supposedly it took the developer several tries as well, but I've done a dozen variations and keep getting wiped out."
